    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-2273440">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-2273440">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2273440)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2273440">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="1324229"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1429454514 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">19 Apr 2015 14:41</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2273440">
									

<p>There's too much goofy shit, like having the main character named <em>Aleksander Foxx</em>, for me to take this seriously. It's too boring for me to appreciate it as goofy fun. The characters are too flat for me to appreciate it as a character piece. The writing is the weakest that I've seen in the series so far<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-436160-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-436160-1')">1</a></sup> with bizarre flourishes like &quot;sea-black coffee,&quot; &quot;and an elderly man waltzed in,&quot; and &quot;smiled a wicked grin&quot; pulling me out of the story at pretty much every other line.</p>
<p>There were some moderately interesting aspects to the story, and there's some stuff that you mentioned earlier that I would like to see explored. But as a piece standing on its own merits, I have to give this a -1.</p>
<div class="footnotes-footer">
<div class="title">Footnotes</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-436160-1"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-436160-1')">1</a>. Which isn't to say it's bad. It's middling. But middling next to &quot;some of the best writers on the site&quot; represents a weird drop in quality.</div>
</div>

							</div>

								
					
